TITLE: The Age of Big Data and the Internet of Things
CG TITLE: The Age of Big Data and the Internet of Things
TVGUIDE: With nearly 20 years of experience in the wireless and high-tech sectors, Daniel Obodovski's passion is helping companies go to market with connected devices and machine-to-machine (M2M) technologies. He has worked with some of the top people in the industry to realize the vision of the Internet of Things. Most recently, Daniel was Director of Business Development at Qualcomm, where he led the commercial launch of multiple M2M products and businesses. Prior to that, Daniel was Director of Strategic Marketing and Business Development at Motorola Germany. In 2011 Daniel co-founded, and currently co-chairs, M2M SIG at CommNexus San Diego. The Silent Intelligence: The Internet of Things Daniel Obodovski is co-author of the recent book, The Silent Intelligence: The Internet of Things. The book covers the history, trends, technology ecosystem and the future of the Internet of Things, Connected Cities, Connected Homes, Connected Health and Connected Cars. It also discuss the most promising areas for entrepreneurs and venture investors sharing the stories and unique opinions of over 30 industry veterans, experts and visionaries from Google, Ericcson, AT&T, Qualcomm, Accenture, SAP, MIT, EcoLife Foundation and many others. Daniel holds an MBA degree from the University of South Carolina and Vienna University of Economics and Business Administration, as well as a Master's degree from the Moscow State Lomonosov University.

TITLE: Peak Moment: 270 - Re-thinking Stress and What You Can Do About It
CG TITLE: Peak Moment: 270 - Re-thinking Stress and What You Can Do About It
TVGUIDE: What people really think of as adrenal fatigue or burnout rarely has anything to do with the adrenals themselves. - Nora Gedgaudas dispels myths, and illuminates various forms of brain dysregulation that can affect our response to stress, as well as our energy levels. She also discusses the importance of a daily sleep-and-activity rhythm based on natural light and dark, a low-carbohydrate diet and supportive supplements. Nora is the author of a new e-book Rethinking Fatigue What Your Adrenals are Really Telling You and What You Can Do About It.

TITLE: Peak Moment: 269-255 Handmade Tools Make Simple Work & Catch The Rain
CG TITLE: Peak Moment: 269-255 Handmade Tools Make Simple Work & Catch The Rain
TVGUIDE: Watch Brian Kerkvliet cut thick grasses easily and quickly with his hand-built scythe  a far cry from a noisy weed whacker! He demonstrates three tools whose design he has honed over the years: the scythe, grass rake and U- bar or broadfork. "It took a few years to get the right methodology, the right blades, the right sharpening technique, and the ergonomic setup so it's effortless," he says of the scythe. The U-bar gently aerates soil and doesn't compress it like a rototiller. "I used to rototill, run my tractor. The beauty of this is you don't have to do the whole area. You just do the beds you need to do. It might take me 15-20 minutes to do these beds, and I'm good for three years. PLUSSavvy Seattleites are capturing rain from their rooftops not only to water their yards, but to slow runoff into the streets. Jim Bristow gives a gutter-to-ground tour of a residential system, including small-profile cisterns tucked beside the house. Jim also shows a "rain garden," which acts as a catch-basin beside the sidewalk. It collects and drains rainwater, which only spills over into the street during severe rain events. Government agencies subsidize the cost of these small systems, which reduce the amount of storm water flooding the city's sewage system, and ultimately flowing into Puget Sound. Locally Reliant Living for Challenging Times

TITLE: Peak Moment: 272 - First Nations People Reclaiming Their Heritage
CG TITLE: Peak Moment: 272 - First Nations People Reclaiming Their Heritage
TVGUIDE: My full name is Pawatsqwachitl. I come from Ahousaht on the west coast of Vancouver Island. Following the indigenous custom, Pawa Haiyupis introduced herself, her people and territory. She thanked the Coast Salish people and territory where we were videoing (Victoria, B.C.) This First Nations woman works with youth, elders and spiritual leaders to practice their culture and "activate their blood memories," as one elder calls it. She says: "We're going on medicine walks, we're doing sweats in safe spaces, and we're learning about our creation stories and sacred sites in our culture." She gives a glimpse of a different way of relating to one another and the Earth from a culture that has been sustainable for many thousands of years.

TITLE: New Life Youth Show

The purpose is to invite all kinds of youth around Portland to come and visit us for our weekly youth services. (First Tuesday of the month in English and the rest in Russian). We also would like to represent the Slavic community in Portland.

CG TITLE: City Club of Portland - Your Genes are not Your Destiny - From Big Data to Personalized Medicine 01/23/15
TVGUIDE: Dr. Leroy Hood helped pioneer the human genome program in 1980s-making it possible to map the human genome with the automated DNA sequencer. Today, Hood is developing strategies and technologies that he views as the basis for a new approach to health - and how doctors might bring together genetics, chemistry, biology, and predictive tools to help patients become more healthy. Will these new approaches improve health outcomes for communities that our current system leaves behind? What are the consequences of making genetic data part of your health record?

TITLE: City Club of Portland - Winter 2015 - Is Oregon's Economy Healed? 02/06/15
CG TITLE: City Club of Portland - Is Oregon's Economy Healed? 02/06/15
TVGUIDE: The economic recovery following the Great Recession in the U.S. has been long and tepid. Recent stronger growth indicates that the Oregon economy has finally emerged from the recession. Are we economically healed or do we have some lingering ailments? Joining us for the program: Dr Thomas Potiowsky, Professor of Economics and Department Chair at Portland State University and Chuck Sheketoff, Executive Director of the Oregon Center for Public Policy.

TITLE: City Club of Portland - Winter 2015 - Raising the Floor: Economic Prosperity for Women & Families 02/13/15
CG TITLE: City Club of Portland - Raising the Floor: Economic Prosperity for Women & Families 02/13/15
TVGUIDE: Nearly 197,000 Oregon workers don't earn enough to cover their basic needs and rely in some part on public support. They are disproportionately women and persons of color, with deep gender and racial disparities. Highlights on new research from the "High Cost of Low Wages" that revealed public assistance to low-wage workers costs $1.7 billion annually. As our low-wage economy grows, what are the impacts on working families? How does Oregon move forward and invest in economic opportunity for all?

TITLE: City Club of Portland - Winter 2015 - Change the Question, Change the World! 02/20/15
CG TITLE: City Club of Portland - Change the Question, Change the World! 02/20/15
TVGUIDE: How can the questions we ask in our day-to-day work significantly enhance the quality of life in our communities?   Social scientist and asker of powerful questions, Hildy Gottlieb, will share what she and her team at Creating the Future have learned in over 15 years of research and experimentation into the factors that create social change. Their key finding: Creating thriving communities is not a matter of innovative new ideas; it is about changing the assumptions that go into those ideas.   The simple act of changing the questions we ask in our day-to-day work can immediately change those assumptions - from assumptions of scarcity to assumptions of "enoughness;" from suspecting the worst in each other to bringing out the best in each other; and most powerfully, from reacting to what's wrong to creating what is possible.

TVGUIDE: With the Portland Police Bureau committed to change under a court-ordered settlement of a Justice Department lawsuit, Portland Mayor/Police Commissioner Charlie Hales is counting on reforming the bureau from within under its new chief, Larry O'Dea, whom he appointed without a search. TITLE: The Best of Safe Smiles (adult)
TVGUIDE: episode 1 "Doo Wop" by Lauryn Hill read by Ezekiel Brown the lyric project is a love letter to songs we (and you) dig. whether it be the song you sing while taking out the trash, that bus stop beat you can't get out of your head, or that song that triggers heart break or joy when you hear the first few seconds. what we want to do is create short films with you! the process is simple. we want you to pick a song that has lyrics you love, i mean love, lyrics that touch you in a funny, uplifting, downtrodden, blitz out of your mind way. it doesn't matter what genre. next, record said lyrics using your phone, or mic set up in a quiet place. then send the audio file to us, along with a brief explanation of why you picked that piece. we will read and listen to your submission. finally we will go out and shoot video that we feel captures that feel of your reading and lyric choice. after that, done, posted, and added to our page. we hope to get many people involved who truly appreciate the sometimes absurdity and beauty of some of our favorite songs lyrics. to start it off, here the first one we did. cheers

TITLE: City Club of Portland - Spring 2015 - Epigenetics and Equity: The Health and Social Impacts of Racism and Inequality 4/24/15
CG TITLE: City Club of Portland - Epigenetics and Equity: The Health and Social Impacts of Racism and Inequality 4/24/15
TVGUIDE: Larry Wallack, Professor and Director for Public Health Studies at PSU, and Rachael Banks, Manager of Healthy Birth Initiatives Oregon Health and Science University runs the world's leading center of study on a new area of science that shows how certain lifetime stresses create inheritable changes in our bodies. The science itself is fascinating. It challenges our prior understanding of evolution and genetic inheritance. We have asked Dr. Wallack to spend the first half of the program focused on telling the story of the science. But the science has major public health consequences - and major implications for public policy that seeks to create equal health outcomes for communities of color. Larry Wallack, Professor and Director for Public Health Studies at PSU, and Rachael Banks, Manager of Healthy Birth Initiatives, are both working on upstream public health policies that would be effected by this new science.
